This is an EFA for the ratings of the self on all items. Only 70 of the 77 have totally complete data, and to be conservative, I’m just looking at those 70. We don’t lose too much without those 7 and it’s easier to satisfy assumptions of EFA without missing data. Haven’t looked closely at what they’re missing yet though.

## [1]  77 239

These histograms by themselves tell a really interesting story – you can see that there is a some overlap between Acc and Cont ratings, but some items distinguish between them. These line up with a lot of our a priori ideas – see anger and jealousy. Pretty cool.

Aside from the status items, you also can see the scores on depression and substance use, among other things. Keep in mind the middle 2 CES_D items are reverse coded. SES ladder is mostly between 3-7 on a 9 point scale.

The scree plot shows very clearly a 4 factor solution will account for most of the variance, with no real gain if we increase beyond 4.

The raw output, if you like, but see below for a prettier table.

The four factors are pretty interpretable, if you ask me.

  1. First (ML2), we have prosociality: caring, fair, helpful, loyal (guidelines for a model girl scout, basically).
  2. Second (ML1), is surgency/dynamism (note that depression is the highest loading item, so positive items are actually given negative loadings): not depressed, lonely, or insecure; trendy, confident, popular, social.
  3. Third (ML3), we have…aggression? Rude, mean, bossy, snobby, as well as lazy and fake.
  4. Finally, fourth (ML4), daring, risky, adventurous, and not rule following.

These factors are allowed to correlate, so if you’re interested, scroll up to the raw output.

Now I correlate self rated accepted and controversial status with these factor scores.

SelfPop_1 is controversial, and SelfPop_2 is accepted.

##                                                                                                                        SelfPop_1
## 1 Think again about high school. For each type, select the option that corresponds to how well it d...-Controversial high status
##                                                                                                                   SelfPop_2
## 1 Think again about high school. For each type, select the option that corresponds to how well it d...-Accepted high status

We see accepted status is highly correlated with the surgency/dynamism component (remember, it’s reversed because of the depression item).

We also see that controversial status is correlated with aggression and slightly with risk-taking.

This gets more interesting in the regressions.
